<h2><span class="icon">👋</span>Welcome to Week 2</h2>

<p>In Week 1, you explored workforce development as a system.</p>

<p><strong>In Week 2, we go deeper.</strong></p>

<p>This session shifts the focus from <strong>who is in the system</strong> → to <strong>how the system produces outcomes</strong>.</p>

<p>Across communities, we see the same pattern:</p>

<ul>
<li>some individuals advance</li>
<li>others remain stuck</li>
<li>many cycle through services without long-term mobility</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>This is not random.</strong></p>

<div class="callout">
👉 These outcomes are shaped by how systems are designed.
</div>

<h3>Why This Matters</h3>

<ul>
<li>access to education and training</li>
<li>labor market structure and job quality</li>
<li>employer hiring practices</li>
<li>availability of supports</li>
<li>policy and funding decisions</li>
</ul>

<div class="callout">
👉 When systems are misaligned, even strong programs struggle to produce lasting outcomes.
</div>

<div class="callout">
<strong>Week 2 Focus:</strong><br><br>
Understanding economic mobility as a system outcome — and identifying where systems enable or limit advancement.
</div>

</section>

<div class="divider"></div>

<!-- OA Framework -->
<section id="oa-framework">
<h2><span class="icon">📊</span>The Opportunity Accelerator Framework</h2>

<p>The OA framework provides a structure for responding to workforce system challenges.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Assess & Plan</strong> → Understanding system conditions</li>
<li><strong>Equip & Connect</strong> → Delivering services and pathways</li>
<li><strong>Launch & Evaluate</strong> → Supporting outcomes and measuring success</li>
</ul>

<h3>Applying OA in Week 2</h3>

<div class="callout">
👉 OA becomes a <strong>lens for analyzing system performance</strong>
</div>

<ul>
<li>Where are outcomes breaking down?</li>
<li>Which SDAs influence those breakdowns?</li>
<li>What design decisions are contributing?</li>
</ul>

<div class="callout">
<strong>system conditions → service design → participant outcomes</strong>
</div>

</section>

<div class="divider"></div>

<!-- Understanding Systems -->
<section id="system">
<h2><span class="icon">🔗</span>Understanding Economic Mobility as a System</h2>

<p>Economic mobility is not a single event.</p>

<p>It is shaped by multiple systems interacting over time.</p>

<h3>Key System Dynamics</h3>

<h4>Structural Inequality</h4>
<p>Access to opportunity is not evenly distributed.</p>

<h4>Labor Market Segmentation</h4>
<ul>
<li>low-wage roles</li>
<li>limited advancement pathways</li>
<li>unstable employment</li>
</ul>

<h4>Racialized Workforce Outcomes</h4>
<p>Outcomes differ across populations due to structural inequities.</p>

<h4>System Design</h4>
<ul>
<li>who enters services</li>
<li>what services they receive</li>
<li>what outcomes are possible</li>
</ul>

<div class="callout">
👉 Economic mobility is produced by systems — not just effort.
</div>

</section>

<div class="divider"></div>

<!-- Systems Thinking -->
<section id="thinking">
<h2><span class="icon">🧠</span>Systems Thinking in Workforce Development</h2>

<p>Systems thinking moves us from symptoms → root causes.</p>

<p>Instead of:</p>
<p>❌ Why aren’t participants succeeding?</p>

<p>We ask:</p>
<p>✅ What conditions are shaping outcomes?</p>

<h3>Core Practices</h3>

<ul>
<li>identify patterns</li>
<li>map relationships</li>
<li>analyze system interactions</li>
<li>identify leverage points</li>
</ul>

</section>

<div class="divider"></div>

<!-- Leadership -->
<section id="leadership">
<h2><span class="icon">👔</span>Systems Leadership in Economic Mobility</h2>

<ul>
<li>see beyond programs</li>
<li>understand system interactions</li>
<li>use data for decisions</li>
<li>align resources</li>
<li>address root causes</li>
</ul>

<div class="callout">
👉 Leadership is about shaping how systems produce outcomes.
</div>

</section>

